1t must be borne in mind that Claudius and his advisere, while thus taking the reins at a moment's notice, succeeded to no such well- ordered empire as had been transmitted by Augustus to Tiberius and by him to Gaius, but to one full of confusion and misgovernment. The bloody deed of Jan. 24 had revived the memory of die ides of March of sc. 44, and had shaken the foundations of Caesarism; the threads of continuity had been snapped, the State had been two days without aprinceps, and the restoration of the Republic had been debated as an open question ³. The executions and extortions of the late tyranny had thoroughly alienated the rich, while the populace, though probably fortunate enough to be ignorant of their peril, and deploring the loss of what must have seemed a golden age of amusements ⁴, were in imminent danger of all the horrors of famine ⁶.
